THE CITY THAT DIDN'T NEED YOU
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE NOTICE
The Disguise
Bjorn pulled the cart to a halt on the last hill before the Rift valley, just out of sight of the city guards. He turned around on the bench and looked at his passengers with the expression of a man who had been herding cats across Skyrim for months and had finally run out of patience.
"Alright, listen up. Riften is paranoid on a good day. If we roll up to the gates looking like this, the guards are going to fill us with crossbow bolts before we can speak. You need to cover up."
He pointed at Davinia. "Keep that ice hand in your pocket and pull your hood down. Don't let them see your eyes."
He pointed at Alfonso. "Wrap that heavy Falkreath cloak tight. You smell like an open grave. If anyone asks, you're recovering from Ataxia. Keep your mouth shut."
He rubbed his temples and looked at Ylva. "And Ylva, by the gods, put some clothes on."
Ylva shifted under the single cloak she'd been wearing since her transformation shredded everything else. "The cloak covers enough. My blood is still running hot from the shift. You try having your ribs shattered and forced back together by wolf-blood in five seconds, and see how much you want to wear tight leather right after."
"I don't care if your blood is boiling. If you walk into Riften bare-assed, the guards will lock you in the dungeon for public indecency before we even cross the bridge. Put on some pants."
Ylva grumbled but dug through the cart's spare supplies and cobbled together something loose enough to not constrict her overheated skin. Modesty remained, at best, approximate.
They covered what they could. Davinia tucked the Wizard Hand into her cloak. Alfonso wrapped himself in wool and silence. Orion adjusted his collar over his fangs. They looked, from a distance, like a group of exhausted travelers instead of a vampire, a lich, an overwriting consciousness, a Daedric-gifted archer, and a werewolf.
Bjorn took up the reins. "Let's go."
The Wall
They saw Riften from a mile out. The autumn canopy of the Rift ΓÇö golden, amber, red ΓÇö framed the city walls exactly as they remembered them from Thornheart Grove. The lake shimmered. The air smelled of damp wood and fermenting honey.
No smoke. No black flags. No barricades.
The north gate was open. Guards stood at their posts, relaxed, chatting. A merchant cart was being waved through without inspection. Children were playing near the road. A woman hung laundry from a line strung between two posts outside the gate.
A guard glanced at Bjorn's cart, recognised the Warden emblem, and waved them through with a nod.
"Welcome back to Riften."
Nothing more.
They rolled through the gates into a city that didn't need saving. The market was open. Madesi was at his stall. Balimund's forge was running. The canal was the same murky green it had always been ΓÇö not black, not poisoned, not choked with bodies. Someone had placed flowers along the railing near the Temple of Mara.
Near the canal bridge, a simple stone marker with names carved into it. The people who died before Danica arrived. Candles and wildflowers around the base. Maybe a dozen names. Enough to be tragic. Not enough to be a catastrophe.
And at the gate, posted on official parchment bearing Maven Black-Briar's seal:
The people of the Rift owe their lives to the courage and devotion of the OBSIDIAN LANTERNS and their priestess DANICA PURE-SPRING. Through her tireless efforts and personal sacrifice, the contagion that threatened our city has been eradicated and our beloved Hemming Black-Briar restored to health. The Black-Briar family extends its eternal gratitude.
Their name. Their company. On the wall. For the greatest act the Obsidian Lanterns had ever performed.
None of them had been in the room when it happened.

PART II: THE SIX POINTS
The Temple
Davinia went to the Temple of Mara alone.
She didn't tell the others where she was going. She pulled her hood down, tucked the Wizard Hand into her cloak, and walked through the market toward the canal district with the specific, tight-shouldered posture of someone walking toward something they were afraid of.
She didn't make it to the temple.
A hand landed on her shoulder in the market stalls. Firm. Not aggressive. The grip of someone who wanted her to stop, not someone who wanted to hurt her.
Krusp Fanck. He was carrying a canvas sack of provisions ΓÇö bread, dried fish, a bundle of healing herbs. Shopping. The last time she had seen this man, he had called her a monster at Kynesgrove and walked away.
He looked at Davinia. His jaw was tight. His hand stayed on her shoulder.
"She doesn't know you're here," he said. Low. Controlled. "Give her the choice. Don't ambush her with this."
Davinia stared at him. "What are you talking about? Why do you care?"
"Because Danica is my friend too."
The words landed before Davinia could process them. Krusp. Here. In Riften. Friends with Danica. The man who had denounced the Wardens as monsters had found the woman Davinia had sent away, and he had stayed.
Behind her, footsteps. Alfonso and Orion caught up ΓÇö they had been following at their own pace, and the sight of Krusp Fanck with his hand on Davinia's shoulder brought them to a stop a few feet back. Krusp glanced at them. His expression didn't change. He didn't acknowledge them, didn't greet them, didn't adjust his posture. They were irrelevant to this conversation.
"Give her the choice," he said again, to Davinia only. Then he let his hand drop and stepped aside.
Davinia kept walking. Alfonso and Orion fell in behind her without comment. Krusp watched them go, then turned back to his shopping.
Danica was at the Temple of Mara, kneeling beside an elderly man, hands glowing with restoration magic, speaking softly. She looked different ΓÇö thinner, tired, visibly aged by the purification ritual that had saved Hemming Black-Briar's life. But the frailty was layered over something new. A calm authority she hadn't carried before. The posture of a woman who had done something impossible and knew it.
She finished with her patient. She stood. She turned.
She had rehearsed this moment. She had six points prepared. She had practiced them with Krusp until they were clean, clear, and indestructible. She was ready.
Then she saw them. Davinia in front, hood drawn. Alfonso and Orion behind her ΓÇö they had caught up during the exchange with Krusp, falling in without comment. Saijah bringing up the rear, quiet, her migraine a low hum in the healthy Rift air.
She counted. Four. There should have been five.
"Where's Kyboh?"
She asked it before anything else. Before the anger. Before the speech. Before the boundaries. She looked at Davinia, then at the space beside her where a loud, reckless Khajiit should have been standing. Her hand moved to her pocket ΓÇö where the note was. Where the paw print was.
They told her. Hjolmar. The Matrix. The light. Gone. They didn't know if he was alive.
Danica listened. Her jaw worked. The healing area was full of patients ΓÇö the elderly man she'd been tending, others waiting, the quiet murmur of people recovering from the plague's aftermath. This was not the place.
Davinia saw it too. "Can we talk? Somewhere alone?"
Danica nodded once. She led Davinia out of the healing area and up the stone stairs to the main prayer hall ΓÇö the heart of the Temple of Mara. The place where weddings happened. High-vaulted ceiling, warm candlelight, the altar of the goddess of love at the far end. Flower garlands from a recent ceremony still hung from the pillars. The room smelled of incense and dried petals.
Two women who had loved each other standing in the room where people promised to love each other forever.
The others waited downstairs. They could not hear what was said. They could only see Davinia's face when she came back.
The Speech
Danica didn't scream. She didn't cry. She was measured, clear, and devastating. Krusp had taught her that boundaries are stated, not begged for.
The six points she had prepared were for a confrontation with people who had abandoned her to play hero. The loss of Kyboh had shifted the ground ΓÇö but not enough. Not nearly enough. Everything Davinia had done at Korvanjund still happened.
"You held my face," Danica said. "I reached for your hands. And you slapped them away. Do you understand what that felt like? I was reaching for you and you hit me."
Davinia opened her mouth. Danica kept going.
"Then you told me to leave. Not 'I need space.' Not 'Give me a day.' You said 'I need you to go.' In the middle of Korvanjund. In a snowstorm. You sent me into the wilderness alone because you were afraid."
She pulled the note from her pocket. Five days of carrying it. She unfolded it, and her eyes caught the paw print at the bottom. Her voice faltered ΓÇö just for a second, just enough to see the crack beneath the wall ΓÇö and she pushed through.
"You compared yourself to your father. The man who shipped you away and called it chess. And then you did the same thing to me."
"You said 'I need you, Danica.' You said 'every step you took away was a dagger in my heart.' But you made me take those steps. You sent me away."
She looked at the paw print again. Her jaw tightened.
"Kyboh signed this. His little paw print. He was the only one who made me feel like the group actually wanted me around. And now he's gone."
The next point landed hardest.
"You decide things for people," Danica said. "You decided I couldn't handle what was happening to you. You decided Korvanjund was too dangerous for me. You decided I should go to Riften. You decided the Crown was your burden to carry alone."
She met Davinia's eyes.
"And every time you decide for someone, you tell yourself it's love. It's not, Davinia. It's control."
Davinia stood very still. The Crown was silent ΓÇö completely, utterly silent. Ismara had nothing to say. For the first time, the absence of the whisper felt like restraint rather than indifference. The ancient researcher knew, with four thousand years of strategic intelligence, that speaking now would destroy everything.
"I am not leaving the Lanterns because I hate you," Danica said. "I am leaving because I am a better healer, a better priestess, and a better person when I am not waiting for you to decide what's best for me."
"I saved this city. I saved Hemming Black-Briar. I performed a ritual that nearly killed me. And I did it without you."
The last point. The door.
"If you want me in your life ΓÇö not as a piece you move around the board, not as someone you send away when things get scary, but as an equal ΓÇö then prove it. Not with notes. Not with symbols. With being here. With staying."
"But I will never again let you hold my face with the same hands that slapped mine away."
The Silence
Davinia was quiet for a long time.
She had gotten defensive at first ΓÇö small deflections, half-explanations about the Crown, about the danger, about why the path she was walking was too dangerous for anyone else to follow. The old pattern. The deciding-for-people pattern. Danica's wall held against every one of them.
Then Davinia stopped talking and listened.
She listened to all six points. She heard them. She didn't have an answer to most of them, and the ones she did have were the wrong answers ΓÇö explanations that proved the point they were meant to refute.
In the end, she doubled down. Not on Danica being wrong. On the Crown being necessary. On the path being too dangerous. On the same logic that had driven Danica away in the first place, articulated differently but built from the same materials.
Danica heard it. She recognised it. Her lip trembled ΓÇö not from weakness, but from the effort of holding the wall in place against a woman she still loved, who was still doing the thing that made her leave.
"Then I think we need time," Danica said. "I'll be here. With Krusp. Doing the work. When you can say 'I was wrong' without telling me why you were right... come find me."
She folded the note and put it back in her pocket. She walked past Davinia, down the stone stairs, back to the healing area where her patients were waiting. The wedding hall was empty except for the candles, the flowers, and Davinia standing alone at the altar of the goddess of love with nothing left to say.
The door was cracked. Not open. Not shut. Cracked ΓÇö the width of a paw print, the size of a possibility that neither of them was ready to walk through.
Davinia came back downstairs. The others saw her face and didn't ask.
Alfonso
After the confrontation ΓÇö after Davinia had left the temple without speaking to anyone and the others had drifted away to process what they'd read in her expression ΓÇö Alfonso found Danica.
She was sitting on the temple steps, not crying, not praying, just sitting with the specific exhaustion of a woman who had just delivered the hardest speech of her life and didn't know if it had made anything better.
Alfonso sat beside her. The corroded rapier hung at his hip. The Jagged Crown sat on his skull. He smelled like grave dirt and old leather, and he was the last person in the party anyone would have expected to offer comfort.
"I think you're making a mistake," he said.
Danica looked at him. She didn't know what she expected ΓÇö agreement, maybe. Condemnation. The cold tactical assessment that Alfonso brought to everything.
"I think leaving is a mistake," he said again. "Not because Davinia deserves you staying. Because the group needs you. And because being needed is worth more than being right."
Danica's composure broke. The tears she hadn't shed during the speech came now ΓÇö not for Davinia, not for the relationship, but for the simple, devastating kindness of a man who had eaten people throughout the entire campaign telling her that she mattered.
She pressed her face against his chest and cried. Alfonso let her. He didn't hug her back ΓÇö he wasn't built for that, and they both knew it. He just sat there, steady and silent, while a priestess wept against the thing that used to be a vampire, and the Crown of Namira's fungal veins pulsed faintly against her hair.
When she pulled away, her eyes were red and her voice was raw. "Thank you, Alfonso."
He nodded once. "Don't leave."
"I have to," she said. "For now."
He accepted it the way he accepted most things ΓÇö with the clinical finality of a man who understood that some diagnoses couldn't be changed by wanting them to change.
The Amulet
Davinia went back to the temple.
She found Krusp inside, kneeling at the altar of Mara. Dawnbringer lay across his knees. His head was bowed, his hands clasped, his lips moving without sound. The candlelight caught the sword's blade and threw warm reflections across the stone floor.
He had arrived after the confrontation. He hadn't been in the wedding hall. He hadn't heard the six points or the silence that followed. But he knew ΓÇö from the way Davinia had come out, from the way Danica had gone back to her patients without speaking, from the specific quality of quiet that follows a conversation where everything important was said and nothing was resolved.
"Krusp."
He didn't look up.
"I need you to give something to Danica for me. An amulet of Mara. I want her to knowΓÇö"
"No."
The word was flat. Final. He still didn't look up.
Davinia's voice sharpened. "This isn't about you. This is about her. I needΓÇö"
Krusp stood. Slowly. Turned to face her. His expression was not angry ΓÇö it was worse than angry. It was the measured, professional coldness of a man who had assessed a situation and rendered judgment.
"I told you at Kynesgrove what I thought of you. Nothing I've seen since has changed my assessment."
"I don't care what you think of meΓÇö"
"I know you don't. That's the problem."
He met her eyes. Held them.
"Do you know who I am? I am Danica's friend. I am the person who was here when you were not. I am the man who stood beside her while she performed a ritual that nearly killed her to save a city full of strangers, while you were underground collecting rocks. I am the person she called when she was alone and terrified and exhausted, because you sent her into the wilderness and went to play archaeologist."
He stepped closer. Not threatening. Present.
"You claim to care about her. You sent her away. You want to send her an amulet through a messenger because you cannot face her yourself ΓÇö because facing her would require saying the words she needs to hear, and you would rather send a symbol than say 'I was wrong.'"
He looked at the amulet in Davinia's hand.
"Deliver it yourself. Or don't. But I am not your courier. I am not your intermediary. And I am not the bridge you burned asking to be rebuilt."
He turned back to the altar. Knelt. Resumed praying.
Davinia said something ΓÇö words that the narrative does not remember, because Krusp did not respond to them. He was praying. He was done.
The Crown hummed. Quietly. Ismara had been listening to every word, and for the first time since the forge, the ancient researcher had heard someone accurately describe Davinia's pattern ΓÇö the deciding, the controlling, the sending-symbols-instead-of-showing-up ΓÇö and Ismara had nothing to add. Not because she disagreed. Because Krusp had just made the case for integration better than she ever could.
Davinia left the temple carrying an amulet nobody would deliver and a silence inside her skull that felt like agreement.

PART III: THE HUNTER'S GIFT
The Scent
After the temple. After the confrontation. After the wounds had been opened and left to bleed in the autumn air of Riften.
Saijah was walking through the lower city when it hit her.
Not the migraine ΓÇö the migraine had eased as they'd entered the Rift, the root network here healthy thanks to Thornheart Grove. For the first time in sessions, the pressure behind her left eye was a murmur instead of a scream.
This was something else.
Her pupils dilated. The dim light of Riften's lower streets ΓÇö already dim, already shadowed by the wooden platforms of the marketplace above ΓÇö became sharp, detailed, saturated with information she hadn't asked for. She didn't just see the dark. She cut through it. The ambient noise of the city faded, replaced by something more immediate: heartbeats. Through the walls. Through the stone. The rhythmic, thumping pulse of every living thing within a hundred feet, layered over each other like a choir singing in the dark.
She could smell the stale sweat of the guards on the platform above. The sharp metallic tang of fear from a merchant who had just been threatened in an alley to her left. The warm, copper-sweet scent of blood ΓÇö old blood, dried blood ΓÇö from a butcher's stall two streets over.
Hircine had not asked permission.
The Lord of the Hunt had granted her a taste of what she could be. A free trial of the Alpha's senses ΓÇö the ability to track anything, anywhere, through darkness and stone and silence. The predator's lens, dropped into her skull like a coin into a slot.
Ylva stopped walking beside her. The werewolf's nostrils flared. She smelled the change on Saijah ΓÇö the primal, undeniable scent of Hircine's favour, fresh and bright, like blood on new snow.
Ylva stepped too close. Into Saijah's space. Her usual boisterous grin was tight, her eyes flashing with something that wasn't playful.
"You smell them, don't you?" Ylva said. "The blood pumping in the dark."
She scoffed, looking Saijah up and down.
"I don't get it. You weep over healthy trees and hesitate on the draw, but the Hunter is offering you the teeth anyway. He gave you the scent."
She leaned in, her voice dropping to a competitive growl.
"You better not waste His gift, Elf. If He's letting you smell the blood, you'd better be the first one to spill it. If you're going to hesitate, get out of my way and let a real wolf eat."
Saijah looked at her. At the territorial intensity in her eyes, the bristling energy of a werewolf confronting someone who had been noticed by the same god.
"Ylva."
"What."
"Chill out. You're being too much."
Ylva blinked. The territorial edge wavered ΓÇö not because Saijah had submitted or competed, but because she had simply refused to engage with the dynamic entirely. You can't win a dominance contest against someone who won't acknowledge the contest exists.
Ylva huffed. Stepped back. The tension didn't resolve ΓÇö it just compressed, settling into a rivalry that would simmer beneath every future encounter where both of them had something to prove.
The heartbeats continued. Saijah could still hear them ΓÇö every pulse, every breath, every living thing in her radius mapped and catalogued by senses a Daedric Prince had installed without asking. The gift was intoxicating. The gift was terrifying.
And Kynareth, behind her stone walls, said nothing at all.

PART IV: THE BLACK-BRIAR
Maven
Maven Black-Briar summoned them to the Bee and Barb the following morning. She did not come to them. They came to her.
She sat at her usual corner table, flanked by two housecarls, drinking Black-Briar Reserve from the uncontaminated stock. Her expression was amused. Controlled. She considered the Lanterns useful ΓÇö they had handled Thornheart Grove competently and their agent had just saved her son.
"The Obsidian Lanterns. Back in my city. How nice."
Davinia started to ask about payment.
Maven raised an eyebrow. A slight smile ΓÇö not cruel, genuinely entertained.
"Your woman already collected. Ten thousand gold, my personal favour, and the Aegis. Rather efficient for a lone priestess, wouldn't you say?"
The sentence landed in the space between them like a stone dropped down a well.
"The contract was fulfilled by a member of your company bearing your name. I consider the debt settled."
She let them absorb that. Then she leaned forward, and the amusement drained from her face.
"I have a new problem. Someone poisoned my Meadery. Your friend Krusp handled the muscle, but the architects of this scheme are still out there. I want names. I want to know how they got into my operation. And I want to know who else they've compromised in the Rift."
She set down her glass.
"Five thousand gold for actionable intelligence on whoever did this. The Meadery's sealed lower vats are at your disposal for investigation. My people will give you access."
They accepted.

PART V: THE FORGE AND THE DEAD DROP
Balimund
They spent the better part of a day at Balimund's forge.
The smith was a broad-shouldered Nord with hands like shovels and the quiet competence of a craftsman who had been doing the same work for thirty years and had never once produced something he was ashamed of. His forge was running when they arrived and it was still running when they left.
Seven thousand gold changed hands over the course of the afternoon. Armour repairs, weapon improvements, new equipment for the members who had lost gear in Mzinchaleft, replacement arrows for Saijah's depleted quiver. Balimund worked steadily, without complaint, asking only the technical questions he needed to do the job right.
Davinia ordered an engraving on her ebony mace. The symbol of Mara ΓÇö the goddess of love, of compassion, of the bonds between people. Balimund threw in the engraving for free, courtesy of the fifty-gold tip she'd included in her purchase.
The symbol was small. Precise. Carved into the mace's striking face, where it would press into everything the weapon touched. A prayer embedded in violence. A declaration of faith from a woman whose own faith ΓÇö in herself, in her relationships, in her capacity to love without controlling ΓÇö had just been systematically dismantled by a priestess at the Temple of Mara.
The engraving glowed faintly when Balimund handed the mace back. Not enough to notice in daylight. Enough to see in the dark.
Something had noticed.
The Dead Drop
Davinia was walking through the market afterward ΓÇö hood drawn, ice hand tucked into her cloak, moving through the crowd with the mechanical purpose of someone who didn't want to stop because stopping meant thinking ΓÇö when a street urchin bumped into her.
The boy was small, filthy, quick. He mumbled an apology and disappeared into the crowd before she could react. She felt the weight in her pocket ΓÇö a heavy iron key wrapped in stained parchment that hadn't been there before.
She unfolded the note in a doorway, reading the intent beneath the jagged, frantic handwriting the way she read everything now ΓÇö not as words but as compressed meaning.
The intent was terror. Urgency. A man at the end of his options, gambling everything on a message delivered by a child to a stranger.
You killed the beasts of Kynesgrove and the Pale. But the Golden Eagles took my shield in Riverwood, and now they are in the sewers looking for me. The World-Eater wakes. I know how to kill the black god. If they find me first, the world burns. The Warrens, bottom level. Use the key. Hurry.
Davinia read it twice. The second reading told her more than the first ΓÇö not the words, but the shape of the desperation that had written them. Someone hiding. Someone hunted. Someone who knew things about dragons that the hunters wanted buried.
She pocketed the key and went to find the others.

PART VI: THE RATWAY
The Descent
The sewer entrance was a wooden door set into the foundation beneath the marketplace platform. The smell hit them before they were through it ΓÇö wet stone, rotting food, and something acrid beneath that caught in the throat.
The tunnel split at a junction. A crude sign pointed left with a painted tankard and right with a painted skull. Sitting on an overturned barrel at the fork was a wiry Breton man with a crossbow across his knees.
He watched them come down the stairs with flat, patient eyes.
"That's far enough."
Ten gold a head. They paid. He pocketed the coin, jerked his thumb toward the Flagon, and went back to watching the stairs.
When they left hours later, passing him on the way out, Dirge nodded once.
"Lanterns."
They nodded back.
"Dirge."
It would become a tradition.
The Flagon
The tunnel opened into a vast underground cistern ΓÇö lantern light reflecting off black water in channels that ringed the chamber. At the center, on a raised stone platform, someone had built a tavern. Actual tables. Actual chairs. A bar made from a repurposed merchant's counter. A fire burned in a stone pit, and the smoke curled upward through a vent in the ceiling.
A broad-shouldered Nord with red hair sat in a high-backed chair by the fire like it was a throne. Brynjolf ran the Thieves Guild's Riften operation. He was Maven's primary criminal lieutenant. He looked at them the way a shark looks at a school of fish ΓÇö warm, expansive, friendly in a way that served his purposes entirely.
"Well, well. The Obsidian Lanterns, in the flesh. Or... most of them."
He counted heads. Noticed Kyboh's absence. Didn't press.
"What brings Riften's heroes to its least reputable establishment? And don't say 'the ambiance.'"
They talked. Brynjolf confirmed what they needed ΓÇö the Thalmor kill squad, four elves, well-armed, heading down toward the Vaults to find an old scholar who had been paying rent in decades-old gold coins. The scholar's name was Esbern. He had been down there for thirty years.
Orion gathered his own intelligence separately ΓÇö the orphanage, the pipeline, the Guild's arrangement with Grelod. Information that filed itself away behind his eyes, next to the contract in his pocket and the ring burning cold on his finger.
They moved deeper.

PART VII: THE WARRENS
The Forgotten
Below the Flagon, the light died. The Warrens were not a tavern or a guild hall. They were a shantytown built into abandoned sewer infrastructure ΓÇö makeshift shelters of salvaged wood and canvas, tallow candles wedged into cracks for light, the air thick with skooma smoke and despair.
People lived here. Shapes huddled against walls under layers of rags. An Argonian woman sat against a pillar, staring at nothing, her scales dull and flaking. Two Nord men shared a skooma pipe in a doorway. A child ΓÇö human, maybe eight ΓÇö darted between shelters carrying a clay jug of water.
The tunnel ahead showed fresh damage. A wooden door kicked off its hinges. A shelf of possessions swept to the floor. Someone had come through fast and violent and hadn't cared what they broke.
Against the far wall, slumped in an alcove, a body. Not a Warren resident ΓÇö the clothes were too good. Travel-worn leathers, a courier's satchel, a short sword still in its scabbard. The throat cut with surgical precision. Fresh. Hours old.
His hand was still reaching for the satchel.
The Courier
They searched the body and found two things that changed everything.
A sealed letter bearing the mark of the Blades ΓÇö a stylized diamond pressed into wax. Addressed to Esbern. Written by a man named Caius Varro, who had died ten feet from delivering it.
The letter described a place called Sky Haven Temple, hidden in the Karthspire in the Reach. Inside it, carved in stone by the Akaviri themselves: Alduin's Wall. A complete prophecy. A description of a Shout that could force a dragon from the sky. And something else ΓÇö something the Blades hadn't expected. The Wall depicted a council. A gathering of heroes who were not Dragonborn. The Akaviri had foreseen a world where the Dragonborn fails.
They had prepared for it. For the party's exact situation.
The second item had slipped under the body during the struggle ΓÇö a Thalmor dispatch case, oiled leather, sealed with the Aldmeri eagle. The seal was already broken. Caius had intercepted it before they killed him.
Inside, three documents that Davinia read through Ismara's eyes ΓÇö not as Aldmeris script but as compressed intent, the meaning arriving fully formed, bypassing language entirely.
The Thalmor were allowing the Dagon cult to corrupt the Eldergleam. Deliberately. The weakening of Skyrim's root network served their strategic objectives. A letter to all field commanders: Let the cultists do the foundational work. We will harvest the result.
And worse. Much worse. The Tower Protocol. The Thalmor's true objective was not conquest. Conquest preserved the structure of the world. Their objective was dissolution. The unbinding of the metaphysical anchors that held the mortal plane together. The end of physical existence for every being bound to it.
The cost to the mortal races is total. This is not a side effect. This is the intended outcome.
And a list. Tracked individuals. The Obsidian Lanterns ΓÇö priority observation. Dragon-killers. Politically unstable. The Imperial woman as leverage against her father. The vampire as a biological weapon. The Khajiit, neutralised. The elf-priestess, a Kynareth conduit ΓÇö monitor for Tower Protocol implications.
Esbern ΓÇö last known Blade. Location: Riften Ratway. Extraction team deployed. He cannot be allowed to find Alduin's Wall.
Krusp Fanck ΓÇö independent Dragon Cult hunter. Effective but uncontrollable. Recommend: terminate if he interferes.
They were all on the list. Every one of them. Watched, categorised, assessed for threat level by an intelligence apparatus that wanted to end the world and had written the paperwork to do it.
The Shadows
Orion drifted away from the group.
He moved through the Warrens the way Varon had taught him ΓÇö not invisible, not stealthy, just unremarkable. A shadow among shadows. The skooma addicts didn't look up. The residents had learned not to notice things.
The Argonian woman was sitting against her pillar, staring at nothing. Her scales were dull, her eyes empty, her body a shell that skooma had hollowed out and left standing.
Orion approached her. He said something ΓÇö quiet, intimate, the specific tone of a man offering coin for company. She followed him into the shadows between two shelters, because she had been following men into shadows for years and the transaction was the only thing she understood anymore.
Two Nord addicts in a nearby doorway watched them go. They noted the direction. They went back to their pipe.
Nobody came out.
Orion emerged alone several minutes later. He left forty gold on the ground near the entrance ΓÇö payment for a service rendered, or guilt money for a service taken. His lips were wet. His ring was cold. He rejoined the group without comment.
The addicts, later, investigated. They found the Argonian woman pinned to the wall by an ice spike through her skull. They took the forty gold. They did not report it.
