"Because you saw me look at that girl," Bjorn said. "When we came up from the Ratway. You saw what happened to my face. And you're smart enough to know that wasn't just a man worried about a child's safety."
He poured himself another cup.
"And because Kyboh is gone," he said. "And I had started to think of him as mine. The way you start to think of someone as yours when they're reckless and loud and stupid and they remind you of who you were before you understood that being reckless and loud and stupid gets people killed."
He drank.
"He reminded me of myself when young. Before the Pale Pass. Before I learned what fast was for." He shook his head. "And then the machine took him, and I wasn't there, and I couldn't run fast enough to change it because I wasn't even in the right building when it happened."
He turned to look at her directly.
"We're going to get him back," Bjorn said. It wasn't a question. It was the specific inflection of a man who had failed to say these words once before and had spent forty years understanding the cost.
Davinia looked at him. She thought about the amulet in her cloak. About the wedding hall and the six points and the door cracked to the width of a paw print. About the list in the Thalmor dispatch case and her father's name in the subtext of every line of it. About the Crown's silence, which had stopped feeling like restraint and started feeling like something that watched her think and kept its opinions to itself because it had decided, for reasons she didn't fully understand, that watching her think was more useful than directing her.
"We're going to get him back," she said.
The fire burned. The canal moved outside. They sat together in the way that people who have nothing left to perform sit together ΓÇö the warmth of proximity without the burden of it, two people with old damage and new losses, sharing the specific silence of those who have run at things they couldn't outrun and arrived too late and kept moving anyway.
At the bar of the Bee and Barb, in a city that had saved itself without them, the Obsidian Lanterns sat with their carter and did not speak about the things that mattered and understood each other perfectly.

The next morning brought cold fog off the lake. Three choices. Three directions the world needed them to go.
Klimmek at the bar, nursing his second ale, describing the faces of horn and fire.
A Stormcloak soldier recovering in an upstairs room, dying of something one of them had made.
An old scholar surrounded by thirty years of preparation, asking for a stone tablet from a barrow.
And Mila, pressing a loose nail with one finger on the cart outside, learning what morning looked like when it came through open sky.


